trong legal systems, many of these mechanisms continue under the shadow of the law. Numerous case studies and empirical investigations have demonstrated the variety, importance, and merits, and drawbacks of such institutions. This book builds on these studies and constructs a toolkit of theoretical models to analyze them. The models shed new conceptual light on the different modes of governance, and deepen our understanding of the interaction of the alternative institutions with each other and with the government's law. For example, one model explains the limit on the size of social networks and illuminates problems in the transition to more formal legal systems as economies grow beyond this limit. Other models explain why for-profit enforcement is inefficient. The models also help us understand why state law dovetails with some non-state institutions and collides with others. This can help less-developed countries and transition economies devise better processes for the introduction or reform of their formal legal systems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness enterprisesxLaw and legislationxDeveloping countries. 0aBusiness enterprisesxLaw and legislationzDeveloping countries. 0aBusiness enterprisesxLaw and legislation. 0aContractsxDeveloping countries. 0aContractszDeveloping countries. 0aContracts. 0aCorporate governancexDeveloping countries. 0aCorporate governancezDeveloping countries. 0aCorporate governance. 0aCorporation lawxDeveloping countries. 0aCorporation lawzDeveloping countries. 0aCorporation law. 0aEconomic policy. 0aInternational cooperation. 0aRight of propertyxDeveloping countries. 0aRight of propertyzDeveloping countries. 0aRight of property. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / General.2bisacsh1 aBlundell, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l